---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';

// Tool metadata
const name = "Speaker Phase Tool";
const category = "audio";
const tier = "Audio Utilities";
const description = "Test speaker polarity and diagnose phase issues with our free Speaker Phase Tool. Check speaker phase cancellation, wiring, and phase switch alignment.";
const pageTitle = "Speaker Phase Tool - Online Speaker Polarity & Phase Tester";
const canonicalUrl = "https://boardtools.app/tools/audio/speaker-phase";
const ogImage = "/og/speaker-phase.png";
const keywords = "Speaker Phase Tool, speaker phase, speaker phase plug, speaker phase tester, how to check speaker phase, speaker phase cancellation, speaker phase test app, speaker phase issues, speaker phase switch";
---

<Layout 
  title={pageTitle}
  description={description}
  toolName={name}
  toolCategory={category}
  keywords={keywords}
  canonical={canonicalUrl}
  ogImage={ogImage}
  ogType="website"
  hideBanner={true}
>
  <!-- FAQ Page JSON-LD Schema -->
  <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "what is speaker phase",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>Speaker phase refers to the timing and polarity relation between two or more audio speaker units. When multiple speakers reproduce the same audio signal, their cones should move forward and backward in unison (in-phase). If one speaker's polarity is inverted relative to the other, they operate out-of-phase, causing sound waves to cancel each other out.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "how to test speaker phase",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>You can test speaker phase using our free online Speaker Phase Tool. Play a low-frequency tone (between 40 Hz and 80 Hz) or pink noise through your sound system. Toggle between the In-Phase and Out-of-Phase modes. If the bass is noticeably louder and fuller in the In-Phase mode, your speakers are in-phase. If the bass disappears or gets weaker, they are out-of-phase.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "how to check speaker phase",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>To check speaker phase, sit directly in the center of your stereo speakers and play a mono test signal, such as low-frequency sine waves or correlated pink noise. In-phase speakers produce a strong, centered audio image with full bass. Out-of-phase speakers produce a wide, unfocused soundstage with a hollow center and severely diminished low frequencies.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "how to tell if speaker is out of phase",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>You can tell if a speaker is out of phase by listening for a lack of bass response, a muddy mid-range, and an unstable center image where vocals feel like they are coming from the sides rather than the center. You can also visually inspect speaker wiring to check if the positive (+) terminal of your amplifier connects to the negative (-) terminal of one of the speakers.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "speaker out of phase how to fix",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>To fix a speaker that is out-of-phase, turn off your audio receiver or amplifier and inspect the speaker wires. Ensure that the positive (+) output terminal (usually red) on the amplifier connects to the positive (+) terminal on the speaker, and the negative (-) terminal (usually black) connects to the negative (-) terminal on the speaker. If they are crossed, swap the connections on one of the speakers to restore proper polarity alignment.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "how to optimize speaker phase alignment",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>To optimize speaker phase alignment, position your speakers symmetrically relative to your primary listening position to avoid acoustic delays. For subwoofers, use a speaker phase switch or a variable phase control dial on the subwoofer amplifier panel to adjust the phase angle (from 0 to 180 degrees) until the crossover frequency range sounds punchy, seamless, and fully integrated with your main monitors.</p>"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  </script>

  <!-- SEO JSON-LD WebApplication Schema -->
  <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
