        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">
          1. Understanding Phase & Polarity
        </h4>
        <p>
          Each audio wave is a cycle of pressure increases (peaks) and decreases (troughs). If two speakers receive the same electrical signal, their cones move forwards and backwards in harmony (In-Phase). If one speaker wire terminal is reversed, one speaker cone pushes while the other pulls.
        </p>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">2. The Test Procedure</h4>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-4 flex flex-col gap-1 mt-1">
          <li><strong>Step A:</strong> Play a low frequency (e.g. 60Hz) in In-Phase mode. Listen to the bass intensity.</li>
          <li><strong>Step B:</strong> Switch to Out-of-Phase mode. If the bass drops significantly, your speakers are wired correctly!</li>
          <li><strong>Step C:</strong> If the bass gets <i>louder</i> in Out-of-Phase, one speaker polarity is reversed. Swap the positive (+) and negative (-) speaker wires on one speaker.</li>
        </ul>

        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary">3. Pure Tone vs. Pink Noise</h4>
        <p>
          Sine waves are great for subwoofers and low bass drivers since cancellation is distinct. Pink noise is also useful because it contains all audible frequencies, making phase mismatches audible across mid-range and high frequency tweeter drivers too.
